subject: Re: [junit] manipulation of result.
msgSnippet: Bhavani, JUnit will print a . foreach test case, prior to calling calling setUp() for that test case.  If there was an error or failure, it will print either
messageBody:
Bhavani,

JUnit will print a "." foreach test case, prior to calling calling setUp()
for that test case. If there was an error or failure, it will print either
"E" or "F" after calling tearDown() for that test case.

In your case, the "." before test case 6 indicates the start of test case 6.
Your email doesn't show it, but I believe there is a "." before your test
case 10 that indicates the start of test case 10. Typically you wouldn't
have any output in your tests and the JUnit output would look like this:

.F.E..E..

Each "." indicates the start of a test case. The "F" indicates one failure
and the two "E"s indicate two errors. After all of the tests run, there
should be some details of which ones got failures or errors followed with a
summary of how many tests ran. At least that's what I get with JUnit 3.6.

Here is a sample of my output:

...................F.....F....
Time: 27.181
There were 2 failures:
1) testcase_5_47(PScreateAgent) "expected:<-1> but was:<1>"
2) testcase_5_52(PScreateAgent) "expected:<-1> but was:<1>"

FAILURES!!!
Tests run: 28, Failures: 2, Errors: 0

Larry
